# Project Context

## Purpose
Chang Store is a browser-based Virtual Fashion Studio for fashion brands, stylists, and e-commerce operators. The single-page app lets teams upload garment and subject photos, quickly generate AI-enhanced try-ons, lookbook shots, background swaps, and promotional video clips without needing a separate backend.

## Tech Stack
- Vite 6 + React 19 + TypeScript 5.8 SPA (entry files `index.html`, `index.tsx`, `App.tsx`).
- Tailwind utility classes are loaded via the CDN script in `index.html`, along with custom global styles for scrollbars and widgets.
- State management uses React Contexts (`contexts/`) for language, API keys/models, image gallery, and viewer coordination.
- API/service layer lives in `services/` and wraps Google Gemini (`@google/genai`), AIVideoAuto, and ImgBB via `axios`.
- Build tooling is stock Vite with `@vitejs/plugin-react`, path alias `@` (see `vite.config.ts`), and environment injection for `GEMINI_API_KEY`.

## Project Conventions

### Code Style
Write React components in TypeScript using functional components and hooks. Keep indentation at 2 spaces, prefer descriptive prop names, and colocate CSS via Tailwind utility classes directly in JSX. Use the `@/` alias for root-relative imports instead of long relative paths. Keep stateful logic in hooks or contexts (`hooks/`, `contexts/`) and keep components in `components/` presentational whenever possible.

### Architecture Patterns
`App.tsx` orchestrates feature modules through the `Feature` enum and toggles entire sections instead of conditional routers. Cross-cutting state (gallery, language, API credentials, viewer state) is provided near the root via context providers to avoid prop drilling. Feature logic is split into reusable services under `services/` (e.g., `services/aivideoautoService.ts`) so UI layers only handle orchestration. Copy and localization strings live under `locales/`, and specification work sits under `openspec/` for planning/governance. When adding new functionality, prefer creating focused components (e.g., `components/VirtualTryOn.tsx`) and keep API integrations isolated to maintain clear seams for mocking later.

### Testing Strategy
There is no automated test runner yet; rely on manual flows covering upload, gallery management, API switching, and each AI feature. Before adding automated coverage, introduce Vitest + React Testing Library so we can cover services (mocking remote APIs) and complex components. Until then, document manual QA steps in proposals/tasks and validate critical user journeys (virtual try-on, lookbook generation, video generation, and gallery editing) before merging.

### Git Workflow
Follow the OpenSpec-first workflow documented in `openspec/AGENTS.md`. Significant capabilities, architectural shifts, or behavior changes must start with a change proposal under `openspec/changes/<change-id>/` and go through review/approval before implementation. Commits use short Conventional Commit prefixes (e.g., `feat: add lookbook variations`, `fix: pose library selection`, `chore: update deps`). Branch from `main` (or the active feature branch), keep PRs scoped to approved proposals, and include manual test notes plus screenshots/GIFs for UI work.

## Domain Context
The app is an AI assistant for virtual fashion production: it includes Virtual Try-On, Lookbook Generator, Background Replacer, Pose Changer, Swap Face/Image Recreation, Photo Album Creator, Outfit Analysis & Redesign, Relight, Upscale, multi-mode Video AI (single-shot, continuity planning, GRWM clips), Image Editor, and Inpainting. Users frequently juggle multiple AI providers, so the Settings modal (Header -> editor icon) lets them store API keys/models per provider, while the Gallery surfaces uploaded/generated assets for reuse across tools. Language support currently only includes English, but `LanguageContext` is ready for additional locales by extending `locales/*.ts`.

## Important Constraints
- Environment secrets belong in `.env.local` (e.g., `GEMINI_API_KEY`) or are entered at runtime; never commit keys (ApiProvider persists Google keys to `localStorage`).
- All video-generation features must resolve to `aivideoauto--` models (see `contexts/ApiProviderContext.tsx`), otherwise the service layer raises user-facing errors.
- ImgBB is the only image-hosting backend today, capped at 32 MB uploads; failures should surface meaningful errors and optionally fall back locally.
- The SPA runs entirely client-side, so long-running generation calls happen directly from the browser; always handle latency, safety blocks, and quota issues gracefully via the error helpers defined in `locales/en.ts`.
- Follow OpenSpec governance: new capabilities or behavior changes require approved proposals before coding, and `openspec/changes` must be updated/validated before implementation lands.

## External Dependencies
- Google Gemini (`@google/genai` via `services/apiClient.ts`) powers text-to-image, image-edit, and analysis flows; we lazily initialize a singleton per API key.
- AIVideoAuto (`services/aivideoautoService.ts`) produces both stills and motion; tokens, image models, and video models are stored in context to enforce consistency.
- ImgBB (`services/imageHostingService.ts`) is the current image upload/hosting service for gallery persistence.
